+# Code availability
+
+## Verbatim statement
+
+> The PyPSA-Eur-Sec model is available under MIT license via Github https://github.com/PyPSA/pypsa-eur-sec. Model documentation https://pypsa-eur-sec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/. All the technology assumptions are available via Github https://github.com/PyPSA/technology-data, version v0.3.0 is used in this study. The source code and input data for this study are openly available at Zenodo https://zenodo.org/record/6645232#.Yt6L6tJBwkI under a CC-BY-4.0 license.
+
+## Structural classification
+
+| Field | Classification | Evidence |
+|---|---|---|
+| Has code DOI? | yes | The study source code and input data are stated to be available through Zenodo record 6645232. |
+| Has repository? | yes | The statement lists PyPSA/pypsa-eur-sec and PyPSA/technology-data on GitHub. |
+| On-request clause? | no | The statement says the model, assumptions, source code, and input data are openly available. |
+| Source Data file? | not a publisher Source Data file | Code and input data are provided through Zenodo and GitHub, not as a Zotero Source Data attachment. |
+| FAIR-compliance assessment | high for access, medium for exact reproducibility until checked | Public repositories, documentation, MIT license for model, Zenodo archive, and stated technology-data version v0.3.0 support reuse; ingest did not rerun the workflow. |
+
+## Lesson for my own CA statements
+
+Lesson: Separate model repository, documentation, technology-assumption repository, exact version, and study archive. For Henry's work, add commit hashes and the exact command sequence when feasible so the statement supports reproduction, not only access.
